    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:04410b16-6db9-40e3-9305-dce3a1894162",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 13-year-old Czech girl with a slender build, shoulder-length brown hair often falling across her face, and an energetic, restless manner that is immediately apparent upon entering the consultation room. She rarely sits still for more than a few minutes, frequently tapping her feet, twirling her pen, and glancing around the room [SNOMED:F90.0]. Her teachers and parents describe her as extremely distractible, often unable to complete tasks or follow multi-step instructions at school [SNOMED:F90.0].\n\n{patientName} attends the 8th grade at a public základní škola (primary school) in Brno. Her academic performance has deteriorated over the last two years despite above-average intelligence—she frequently loses homework assignments, forgets deadlines, and struggles to maintain focus during lessons [SNOMED:F90.0]. She has a cognitive deficit in attention that is most pronounced in structured classroom settings [SNOMED:F90.0]. Her teachers have noted a pattern of emotional impulsivity: she blurts out answers, interrupts others, and becomes quickly frustrated when corrected [SNOMED:F90.0].\n\nOutside of school, {patientName} is passionate about street dance and spends several evenings each week at a community dance studio. She enjoys online gaming and manga comics. She has a close group of three friends, though she has had repeated conflicts stemming from her emotional impulsivity [SNOMED:F90.0]. Her mother reports that she has significant difficulty with productive executive tasks—planning, initiating homework, and organising her school bag—consistent with the executive dysfunction described in her diagnosis [SNOMED:F90.0].\n\n{patientName} lives with her mother, father, and a younger brother in a mid-sized apartment in Brno. The household is generally supportive but stressed by her behavioural difficulties. Bedtime is a persistent struggle; she often lies awake ruminating and has chronic sleep-onset difficulties, which exacerbate her daytime inattention. Her diet is unremarkable, and she does not use alcohol or tobacco."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:4ecb673e-1dd5-4bac-807a-c54023b53823",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} was born at term after an uncomplicated pregnancy. Developmental milestones were met on time, though her parents recall she was always a highly active toddler with a short attention span. Concerns about attention and distractibility were first raised by her primary-school teacher when she was 8 years old [SNOMED:F90.0]. A formal psychological assessment was completed at age 10 at a pedagogical-psychological counselling centre (pedagogicko-psychologická poradna) in Brno, which identified significant cognitive deficit in attention and executive dysfunction consistent with F90.0 [SNOMED:F90.0].\n\n{patientName} has no prior hospitalisations and no significant medical comorbidities. She has a known allergy to penicillin (urticaria). Sleep-onset insomnia is a longstanding issue, likely secondary to her attentional disorder; melatonin was introduced to address this. She has never smoked, used alcohol, or any illicit substances. BMI is within the healthy range. Blood pressure and heart rate have been monitored regularly since starting methylphenidate, as stimulant therapy can elevate both parameters. No cardiovascular symptoms have been reported. Family history is notable for ADHD in her father and anxiety disorder in her mother."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
